ice for stabilizing market transactions. How collateral operates, Riles suggests, is paradigmatic of a class of low-profile, mundane, but indispensable activities and practices that are all too often ignored as we think about how markets should work and be governed. Riles seeks to democratize our understanding of legal techniques, and demonstrate how these day-to-day private actions can be reformed to produce more effective forms of market regulation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDerivative securitiesxLaw and legislation. 0aDerivative securitieszJapan. 0aFinancial risk management. 0aOver-the-counter marketsxLaw and legislation. 0aOver-the-counter marketszJapan. 0aSecurity (Law). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  alegal, legality, laws, reasoning, global markets, financial, finances, money, economics, economy, globalism, regulation, governance, governing, government, legislation, legislators, regulators, policy, retail investors, trading programs, ethnography, ethnographic research, transactions, private actions, market, security, law, over the counter, risk management, japan, japanese, collateral, technocratic state, technocracy, hayekian critique, transparency.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022671932040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226719344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226719344/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles